his is the goal of this book. It stands out from the widespread criticisms of meritocracy, by proving how all the rhetoric about performance leads to an irreconcilable contradiction. Lars Distelhorst explains: What can be seen behind the concept of performance is the emptiness of a society whose center lies in the movement of capital accumulation, while she plays the last cards of ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCapitalism. 0aIdeology. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aPower (Social sciences) 0aPower (Social sciences). 4aIdeologie. 4aKapitalismus. 4aKultur. 4aLeistungsgesellschaft. 4aNeoliberalismus. 4aPolitik. 4aPolitikwissenschaft. 4aPolitische Theorie. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aCulture.  aNeoliberalism.  aPolitical Ideologies.  aPolitical Science.  aPolitical Theory.  aPolitics.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/transcript.9783839425978zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839425978zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839425978/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA